(thirdQuint)Community Empowerment to Pilot a Novel Device for Monitoring Rescue Medication Use in Urban Children With Asthma.

 The primary study objective is to measure the effectiveness of using an innovative tracking system (CareTRx) for the self-management of asthma, including daily and rescue medication use, among children with asthma.

 The study objectives will be achieved using a pre-post design for the participants.

 The investigators aim to enroll at least 26 participants for a 3-month intervention period.

 With this pilot study, the investigators hope to examine the impact of self-management behaviors on health outcomes including asthma symptoms and quality of life measures.

